Methods and hypothesis

Problem approach method: Hypothetico-deductive method (Popper, 1979)
Procedure method: Statistical methods

The basic hypothesis to be tested is that populations residing near the equator (latitude 0¬∞) have, on average, a shorter/more morning-oriented circadian phenotype compared to populations living near the Earth‚Äôs poles (Hut et al., 2013; Leocadio-Miguel et al., 2014, 2017; Pittendrigh et al., 1991; Randler, 2008; Randler & Rahafar, 2017; Roenneberg et al., 2003).


\[
\begin{cases}
\text{H}_{0}: \text{R}^{2}_{r} &gt;= \text{R}^{2}_{f} \\
\text{H}_{a}: \text{R}^{2}_{r} &lt; \text{R}^{2}_{f}
\end{cases}
\]

\[
f^{2} = \cfrac{\text{R}^{2}_{f} - \text{R}^{2}_{r}}{1 - \text{R}^{2}_{f}} = \cfrac{\text{Additional Var. Explained}}{\text{Var. unexplained}}
\]

Discussion
A significant p-value (\(\text{p-value} = 2e-16\)) was found, but with a negligible effect size (Cohen‚Äôs \(f^2 = 0.00740\)). Based on these results, we must reject \(\text{H}_{a}\) in favor of \(\text{H}_{0}\).
\[
\begin{cases}
\text{H}_{0}: \text{R}^{2}_{r} &gt;= \text{R}^{2}_{f} \\
\text{H}_{a}: \text{R}^{2}_{r} &lt; \text{R}^{2}_{f}
\end{cases}
\]
It is then possible to answer one of the study main question: Is latitude associated with the regulation of circadian rhythms in humans? Based on these results the answer is no.
